oumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Brook  , which preserves a trace of the Old English dative singular case, originally used after a preposition (e.g. ‘at the brook’).","History: In 1650, Robert and Mary Mainwaring Brooke brought ten children and a number of servants with them from England to MD, where Robert became governor. Although the fourteen known contemporary Brooke immigrants in VA included Robert's brothers Richard and Humphrey, the relationships of the others are unknown. Brooke family memorials remain in the Anglican church at Whitchurch, Hampshire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]}]},{"name":"Arundel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>arondel</i> ‘little swallow’ (a diminutive of <i>arond</i> ‘swallow’, from Latin <i>hirundo</i>).","habitational name from a place so named in West Sussex, from Old English <i>hārhūne</i> ‘horehound’ (a wild plant, <i>Marrubium vulgare</i>) + <i>dell</i> ‘valley’. This place is the seat of the dukes of Norfolk. In northern England, folk etymology resulted in variants such as   Arendale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Arrindell","meanings":["West Indian (Dutch Caribbean and the Dominican Republic): probably an altered form of English   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arrendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel   2."]},{"name":"Arendall","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Arundel De Brooke was born in 1160, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of George Brooke. He had at least 1 son with Edeline de Cobham. He died in 1215, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1180–1231":"1180–1231","1138–Male":"1138–Surnud","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1231":"1231","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1180–1231":"1180–1231","1138–Male":"1138–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1231":"1231","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Décédée","1180–1231":"1180–1231","1138–Male":"1138–Décédé","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1231":"1231","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Arundel De Brooke est né en 1160, à Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de George Brooke. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Edeline de Cobham. Il est dé